data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already threw `InvalidOperationException` on synchronous LINQ by default, but you could opt back in (e.g., `EnableSyncExecution`). **In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** Every sync call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw with no workaround.

## Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`, suffixed with `Async`
- All LINQ terminal operators use their `*Async` counterparts
- `Add()` stays synchronous (it's an in-memory operation; only the DB flush needs async)

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through all callers (controllers, services, etc.) — this is the main migration effort.
